Climate Change Visualization is a '''WebGL'''-based project that aims to visualize surface temperature anomalies over the past century. Inspired by ''Google Chrome Experiments'', this project utilizes data from '''NASA GISS Surface Temperature Analysis (GISTEMP v4)''' to create an interactive globe. The data is based on a 2 x 2 degree grid spacing from the surface air temperature, with 250km smoothing. The project's website layout is adapted from ''Cathal Mc Daid's'' adaptive mobile spam globe.

== Overview ==
The Climate Change Visualization project is designed to provide a visual representation of the changes in surface temperature over the past century. The project uses '''NetCDF''' files from the '''NASA GISS Surface Temperature Analysis (GISTEMP v4)''' dataset, which can be downloaded from the [https://data.giss.nasa.gov/gistemp/ GISTEMP v4 website]. The project's goal is to create an interactive and engaging way to explore the data, making it easier for users to understand the impact of climate change.

=== Features ===
The project features a '''WebGL-globe''' that displays surface temperature anomalies over time. The globe is interactive, allowing users to rotate and zoom in on specific areas. The project also includes a website layout that is adapted from ''Cathal Mc Daid's'' adaptive mobile spam globe, making it accessible on various devices. The project's key features include:
* Interactive '''WebGL-globe''' displaying surface temperature anomalies
* Data from '''NASA GISS Surface Temperature Analysis (GISTEMP v4)'''
* Adaptive website layout for mobile and desktop devices

== Installation ==
To run the Climate Change Visualization project, users can visit the [http://students.washington.edu/aodhan/webgl_globe.html live version] of the project. The project's code is available on '''GitHub''', and users can download the '''NetCDF''' files from the [https://data.giss.nasa.gov/gistemp/ GISTEMP v4 website].

